Git is distributed means everyne have complete copy of code which has version history and who commited what and when.
git init -> initialize new git repo
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
git remote add origin <github_url_of_repo>  -> for github 
git add .
git commit -m <message>
git checkout <branch-name>
git branch <branch-name>
git checkout -b <branch-name>
git push -u origin main

git checkout <commit-id> -> got to a particular commit but don't delete any new commit just head is detached which means head is not pointing to latest commit.
git reset -> if you want to checkout to previous commit as well delete what is after that commit (if can also keep those changes or delete them)
git reset --soft <commit-hash> -> if we do soft reset -. those commits will still be in working directory in staged changes
git reset <commit-id> -> mixed reset -> will keep the changes in working directory but not staged
git reset --hard <commit-id> -> git hard reset discard all after changes

git revert -> undo effects without losing commit history
git revert <commit-id> -> if got conflicts -> resolve and run -> git add . -> git revert --continue

git stash -> let you save uncommitted changes both statged and unstaged
git status list -> to get list of all stashes
git stash apply stash@{0}

Interactive Rebase -> allows you to manipulate commit history
    change a commit's msg
    delete commits
    reorder commits
    combine multiple commits into one
    edit/split an existing commit into multiple new ones
Warning:  do not use interactive rebase on commits that you have already pushed/shared on remote repo
Steps:
    what should be the base commit -> git rebase -i HEAD~3  (will open interactive window to change commit msg)
    In editor only determine which actions you want to perform. Don't change commit data in this step yet.
    
git log -oneline -> check commit mag and hash
To change the lastest commit msg we can just use git ammend but to chnage any commit older than that use rebase

git rebase -i HEAD~3   when interactive winsow come write reword in front of commit msg you want to change it will open another interactive window there we can edit commit msg

to combine 2 commits
Squash keyword -> it will combine the commit and the commit previous to it

Cherry pick-> merge single commit only

git checkout feature/newbranch -> when we need to cherry pick commit from another branch
git cherry-pick <commit-hash>

git reset --hard HEAD~1 -> to delete last master commit

Reflog -> the ref log as git diary. its a journal where git logs every moment of the head pointer.Reflog can also recover deleted commits. we can use the hash

